EMI shielding materials with a high conductivity are better equipped to reflect and absorb harmful EMWs [61]. Therefore, the conductivity is an important characteristic for EMI shielding materials. The conductivities of SM-based adhesives were measured with a four-probe station. As shown in Fig. 5f, the SM/TTE/CDs/BT@PDA@PANI adhesive shows the highest conductivity of 0.231 S m−1, which demonstrates better performance than the majority of conductive adhesives previously described in terms of mechanical properties and conductivity [23]. Furthermore, compared with the other conductive nanoparticles (Ni, Al, and Ag) [62], the resultant adhesive exhibits the highest conductivity even with the lowest loading content of filler (i.e. BT@PDA@PANI). There results could be interpreted by two reasons: 1) The BT@PDA@PANI nanoparticles have intrinsic high conductivity. This is mainly due to the introduction of additional PDA@PANI interfaces into BT@PDA@PANI nanoparticles, and the conductive PANI also provides more carriers, resulting in significant interfacial polarization effects. 2) BT@PDA@PANI nanoparticles are well dispersed within the adhesive matrix, the conductive PANI shell of adjacent nanoparticles can be used as micro electrodes, and a large number of micro electrodes form a micro capacitance network in the polymer matrix. The application of SM/TTE/CDs/BT@PDA@PANI adhesive as efficient EMI shielding materials was further demonstrated. Initially, adhesives were coated onto poplar veneers to produce plywood composites (named SBP, for details, please see Table 1
                        ), and the EMI shielding of the plywood composites in the X-band was investigated (8.2–12.4 GHz). As shown in Fig. 6
                        a, the average EMI SET of SBP2 is higher than 20 dB in the X-band, which can shield almost 99 % of incoming microwave radiation in daily applications. In addition, the thickness of the plywood composites and the number of adhesive layers is also crucial elements that influence the EMI shielding effect. In this study, SBP2 demonstrates an exceptional EMI SET of 38.04 dB in the X-band. This demonstrates that the EMI SET values of SBP plywood composites grow progressively with an increase in adhesive layers under the same thickness (Fig. 6b), which means the number of adhesive layers plays a major role in EMI shielding. Moreover, under the same number of adhesive and veneer layers, the higher the plywood thickness, the higher the EMI shielding. This could be attributed to the multiple interface scattering effect and the plywood hierarchical structure. The large adhesive layer spacing also contributes to the multiple back and forth reflections of EMWs between layers until they are completely absorbed [63]. In addition, SBP2 plywood has substantially higher SEA values than SER values (Fig. 6c). For example, the average SET, SEA, and SER of SBP2 are 38.04, 28.15, and 9.89 dB, respectively, with SEA accounting for 74 % of the total (Fig. 6d), indicating that EMI SE focuses on microwave absorption.
